[normal]Dear Cllrs Davey, Jackson, and Reid,
[normal]As promised in my online response to the Combined Authority local consultation, please find attached further details.
[normal]I am not completely 
[normal]negative about this, but I am extremely concerned that the rural communities of Northumberland and County Durham will have no voice, particularly with regard to public transport, and also because we have already ended up in a unitary county authority witho
[normal]ut residents being able to vote on it.
[normal]Our democratic powers seem to be moving further and further away from us.
[normal]In particular, of the two existing and three proposed combined authorities, 
[normal]Northumberland and County Durham would be the first 2 predominantly[bold] rural authorities[bold] to enter into such an arrangement. 
[normal]I therefore think that there should be two representatives for Northumberland, one for the 50% of the population who live in the southeast and one for the 50% of the population who live in the rural co[bold]mmunities.[bold] Maybe there should be the same arrangement for rural County Durham as well, so that there would at least be some rural voice, even if it was still without any power compared to all of the other urban representatives.
[normal]At the very least, there sho[bold]uld be an effective trial period and means of opting out for the rural areas[bold] of Northumberland and County Durham if this arrangement is found not to be working for them. Before this proposal is allowed to proceed any further there should also be a
[normal] guarante[bold]ed level of service, investment, and protection from cutbacks[bold] for each community, particularly small rural ones, many of which are already left with only the barest remnants of the services which they once had.
